---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { getFeaturedDocs } from "../lib/docs.js";
import "../styles/home.css";

const featured = getFeaturedDocs();
---

<BaseLayout
  title="causal-order | Deployable runtime for distributed event ordering"
  description="Understand and deploy causal-order as a confidence-aware runtime for distributed event ordering, replay, recovery, and streaming reconciliation."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <div class="hero-badge">Deployable distributed runtime</div>
      <h1>A deployable event-ordering runtime for replay, recovery, and distributed event flows.</h1>
      <p>
        <code>causal-order</code> is a deployable event-ordering runtime for distributed systems
        that need bounded replay handling, reconnect-heavy stream reconciliation, explicit
        late-arrival policy, and operator-visible output rather than timestamp-only ordering.
      </p>

      <div class="hero-install">
        <div class="install-kicker">Published on npm</div>
        <div class="install-command">
          <code>npm install causal-order</code>
          <a
            class="install-link"
            href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/causal-order"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
          >
            View package
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/guides/">Read deployment guides</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/wiki/">Explore the wiki</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="hero-panel">
      <div class="signal-card">
        <span class="signal-label">Runtime contract</span>
        <ul>
          <li><code>orderEvents()</code> for bounded replay, recovery, and audit workloads</li>
          <li><code>orderEventStream()</code> for continuous, delayed, and reconnect-heavy flows</li>
          <li>explicit policy for late arrivals, uncertainty, and correction-capable output</li>
          <li>inspection helpers for operator review, downstream writeback, and reconciliation</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="path-strip">
    <article class="path-card panel">
      <span class="card-kicker">Evaluate quickly</span>
      <h2>Decide whether this belongs in a real production flow.</h2>
      <p>
        Start with fit, not implementation. Use the quick-start, supported-usage boundary, and
        real examples before you wire a runtime into a system that has to keep running under
        replay, recovery, and stream pressure.
      </p>
      <ul class="home-links">
        <li><a href="/guides/quick-start-scenarios/">Quick Start Scenarios</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/supported-vs-unsupported-usage/">Supported Vs Unsupported Usage</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/examples-and-entrypoints/">Examples And Entrypoints</a></li>
      </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="path-card panel">
      <span class="card-kicker">Build a first flow</span>
      <h2>Translate, order, and integrate the runtime deliberately.</h2>
      <p>
        Once the fit is clear, move into package surface, policy, and runnable entrypoints that map
        onto actual replay pipelines, recovery jobs, and long-lived stream handling.
      </p>
      <ul class="home-links">
        <li><a href="/guides/package-surface-overview/">Package Surface Overview</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/extension-boundary-guide/">Extension Boundary Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/policy-guidance/">Policy Guidance</a></li>
        <li><a href="/examples/">Examples Index</a></li>
      </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="path-card panel">
      <span class="card-kicker">Run in production</span>
      <h2>Operate deployed ordering under replay, reconciliation, and late-arrival pressure.</h2>
      <p>
        Inspection and operator views support that runtime posture by making deployed ordering
        explainable, reviewable, and honest under real backlog, reconnect, and anomaly pressure.
      </p>
      <ul class="home-links">
        <li><a href="/guides/operations/replay-inspection-workflow/">Replay Inspection Workflow</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/operations/streaming-reconciliation-workflow/">Streaming Reconciliation Workflow</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/operations/incident-review-guide/">Incident Review Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/operations/anomaly-interpretation-guide/">Anomaly Interpretation Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/operations/operator-metrics-guide/">Operator Metrics Guide</a></li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="why-strip">
    <div>
      <span class="card-kicker">Why this exists</span>
      <h2>Production timelines often look cleaner than the system actually was.</h2>
    </div>
    <p>
      Replayed events can look newer than originals. Offline devices sync late. Ingestion order can
      differ from creation order. <code>causal-order</code> is built for systems that still need a
      deployable ordering runtime without turning those realities into false certainty.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="home-grid">
    <article class="home-card">
      <span class="card-kicker">Deployment layer</span>
      <h2><a href="/guides/">Guides</a></h2>
      <p>
        Deployment guides, policy choices, replay workflows, and operator follow-through for the
        current runtime surface.
      </p>
      <ul class="home-links">
        {featured.guides.map((item) => (
          <li><a href={item.href}>{item.title}</a></li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="home-card">
      <span class="card-kicker">Conceptual layer</span>
      <h2><a href="/wiki/">Wiki</a></h2>
      <p>
        Mental models, terminology, and deeper explanations for concurrency, uncertainty, and
        honest ordering claims.
      </p>
      <ul class="home-links">
        {featured.wiki.map((item) => (
          <li><a href={item.href}>{item.title}</a></li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="api-strip">
    <article class="home-card">
      <div class="split-card">
        <div>
          <span class="card-kicker">Runtime reference</span>
          <h2><a href="/api/">API</a></h2>
          <p>
            The runtime entrypoints, inspection helpers, and exported types you build against in
            bounded and streaming deployments.
          </p>
        </div>

        <ul class="home-links home-links-compact">
          <li><a href="/api/translate-batch/">translateBatch()</a></li>
          <li><a href="/api/order-events/">orderEvents()</a></li>
          <li><a href="/api/order-event-stream/">orderEventStream()</a></li>
          <li><a href="/api/inspect-order-result/">inspectOrderResult()</a></li>
          <li><a href="/api/validate-event/">validateEvent()</a></li>
          <li><a href="/api/types/">Types</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
